ownedComment.body: This is the data model for the provenance of observations. It contains the IVOA UML Profile and imports the IVOA_Profile data model with primitive types.
This profile defines the domain specific UML dialect for the IVOA data modelling efforts.

specification.body: Only one end which points to the referenced objecttype is navigable.
Only the referencedEnd has a name.

ownedComment.body: This stereotype indicates that a particular Binary Association End has composition semantics. This is assumed by default for such assiciation ends that are navigable and are not shared. However assigning this stereotype allows one to add some attributes to the relation using tags. To this end the stereotype has tag definitions.

specification.body: Only the composed objects end is navigable.
The composied objects end has aggregationKind = "none"
Only the composed objects end has a name.
Usage dependency exists only from one package to another package.
Between two different entity containment trees no cyclic reference is allowed.

ownedComment.body: Used as the name of the vo-dml model. the uml name is uised as vodml-id.
Defines a custom regular expressions in some language that should apply to the value of the attribute to which the constraint is applied.

specification.body: A base objectytpe is always abstract.or a concrete objecttype is final

ownedComment.body: This stereotype indicates that an atribute represents a term in a particular SKOS vocabulary. This stereotype indicates that a particular Binary Association End has composition semantics. Assigning this stereotype allows one to add some attributes to the relation using tags. To this end the stereotype has tag definitions, in particular the vocabularyURI indicating which particular vocabulary the concept should be extracted from.

This sterotype indicates that a given Property has attribute semantics. This is by default the case for our attributes that must have a datatype cosen form the IVOAValueTypes, howevere the explicit assignment of this stereotype allows the modeller to assign specific extra attributes as tags. For that purpose this stereotype has various tag definitions.

Defines the minimum value an attribute with this constraint may have, i.e. it is inclusive). Can only be applied to attributes whose type has an implied order. Must be defined using a string representation of the value.

Defines the maximum value an attribute with this constraint may have, i.e. it is inclusive). Can only be applied to attributes whose type has an implied order. Must be defined using a string representation of the value.

MinLength defines the minimum length for a string value or the precision for a number.
If MinLength is undefined, then the following rules apply as long as they do not interfer with constraints maxLength or length: - String [0] - Number [Real 4 bytes] for floating point numbers - Number [Integer 4 bytes] for integer numbers

MaxLength defines the maximum length for a string value (or the precision for a number).
If MaxLength is undefined, then the following rules apply : - String [30] - Number [Real 4 bytes] for floating point numbers - Number [Integer 4 bytes] for integer numbers
This guarantees that that value is unique in a collection so a couple (container_id, attribute) must be unique
This attribute must be unique in the Database containing instances of the data model (unique contraints)
Indicates that this field can be used to order a collection of parent class
Any model element can be given this sterotype. It allows one to add some specific labels as tags to the element. For example UTYPE.

If the model element represents an element in another data model, that element can be indicated by adding its UTYPE as this tag's value. Note that we allow an element to have multiple UTYPEs (multiplicity = 0..*).
A package with the name _instances can be used to add example Instance elements to illustrate the model. This package will be ignored in the VO-URP code generation pipeline.
A package defining additional quantities which are used in an IVOA context.

Represents an interval of time from beginning to end. Is not equivalent to s simple real value indicating the number of seconds (for example). In general a custom mapping to a particular serialisation context must be provided.

Represents a complex number, consisting of a real and imaginary component, oth of which are reals. Note that in many contexts there is no native mapping for this type and it must be treated with a custom mapping.
An integer number (from Z).
Represents a moment in time using a date+timestamp. Coordinate reference systems must be defined by the context serialisation.
Represents a decimal number with exact significand such as used to denote monetary values.
A rational number from Q, represented by two integers, a numerator and a denominator. A native mapping to a serialisation context does in general not exists.
A real number (from R).
An integer number from N, therefore greater than or equal to 0.
The standard boolean, having values true or false.
Represents a URI in the same way as the datatype of the same nam in XML Schema is used.
This datatype represents an identifier for an object in the data model. It consists of 3 attributes that each are assumed to work in a particular context or representation of a data model instance.
The id attribute is assumed to represent an object in a database storing instances of the data model.
This attribute is used to support identifing of and referring to an object in an XML document using the ID/IDREF mechanism.

The ivoId attribute is assumed to represent an object in a database following the design of the data model and accessible through a standardised registration and discovery protocols. It is assumed to be unique within the IVOA and its format follows (a generalisation of) the IVO Resource Identifier standard (see http://www.ivoa.net/Documents/REC/Identifiers/Identifiers-20070302.html). Since the ivoId is assumed to represent the resource as registered in a standard database for the data model, it is assumed to be allocated by such a database service. This is in contrast to the use of the IVO Identifier in resource registries, where the id is assumed to be allocated by the publisher. We have the publisherDID attribute for that purpose. Also in contrast to that usage is the fact that each object in the model is assigned this identifier, not only the root resources. We suggest as algorithm for assigning these ivoId to use as root the ivoId of the registered database service, and to append to this a # then the UTYPE of the element and finally its id attribute, separetd from the UTYPE by a forward slash.

This attribute identifies an element in the context of the publisher. It is supposed to be unique in the IVO context and should likely be constrained to have the publisher's authority IVO id. This may need to be rediscussed when protocols for accessing a database built around a data model are to be designed.

A string, represented as an array of characters treated as a single, primitive value. Ala Java, a string can not be updated, that is any update leads to a different string. However in contrast to Java we assume that two strings that are identifcal in all their constitutent characters are the same.
This attribute should hold on to a valid UCD. For that purpose the attribute isa skosconcept, but a proper SKOS vocabulary for UCDs would be required to formalize this further.
Meant to represent the value of a numerical physical quantity. May be integer, what units can apply there?
Must conform to definition of unit in VOUnit spec.

W3C term. An Activity is any kind of link between input and result data. It is a process that acts upon an entity (data), usually with the goal of changing that entity. Here, it is usually an observation or postprocessing of images.
An instance of the Method class which describes how an activity is executed. For one activity there is exactly one description, i.e. the multiplicity is set to 1.
The collection of contacts for an activity. Though is not required to specify a contact, this is a very useful piece of information. Zero-to-many instances are allowed.
A unique id for the Activity so that it can be referred to.
String for naming an Activity. There could be multiple alternative names.
Date/time when the Activity was executed (start time)
Can provide the duration of the execution, i.e. could also contain exposure time for observation (or is this characterisation??) or how long the pipeline needed to process the image/data set.
String that specifies the execution state of an activity. Values for that string could be something like PROCESSING, COMPLETED, etc. Default could be COMPLETED.
A link to the project that is responsible for the Activity. Would be good to have at least one project per Activity, but we won't enforce this.
The collection of input data used to perform an activity. The set of input data usually originates from a previous activity.
Ouput data as produced by an activity. The multiplicity for this activity is set to one to many data components (or data sets).
The Method describes how an Activity is performed. This could be, for instance, the name of the code of a processing pipeline.
Unique id for the Method for referencing.
String to specify the name of a method (e.g. "Flatfielding", "Creating the master bias", name of the code for a pipeline or post-processing)
Free text to shortly describe the method used. (Like 'Protocol' in SimDM.)
A set of type specifications for the zero-to-many input data components.
A specification of the output data component(s),
Processing inherits from Activity. All processing steps like flat-fielding or astrometric calibration are covered by this class.
An instance of the Processor class used to describe the processing pipeline.
Details about the operating system on which the processing was executed.
Processor which inherits from Method describes all activities that belong to the Processing sub-class. General description for e.g. flatfielding, astrometric calibration, imageStacking etc.
Author of the code/processing algorithm/,,, used
Version of the processor (code, algorithm, ...), if applicable. Not mandatory.
Observation inherits from Activity covering all cases in which the result data have been acquired by an (astronomical) observation.
An instance of an ObservationMethod class used to describe how the observation has been done.
The target of an observation, e.g. M31, Star xxx, ...
ObservationMethod which inherits from Method describes all activities that are considered observations.

W3C term. This class defines a contact for a certain activity. Typically this is the person that has performed the activity (allow also institutions??). Details like address etc. could be useful, but at least the current affiliation should be given, so that it's possible to credit the right person/institution for certain tasks or products and to find someone when questions arise. People change affiliations, but it is likely that someone from the old affiliation knows where a person was going to or who else is in charge now.
Name of a person, can also be omitted, if an affiliation or project is given instead.
A string giving the affiliation of the contact for a certain activity.
role of the contact, e.g. owner, publisher, ...

This class is the central component of our composite design pattern. This concept aims at treating the two major groups of data, files and parameter values on the one hand, and complete data set on the other hand, in the same way. The DataComponent class includes the basic properties and functionality (i.e. mainly the interface) for both groups of data.
Link to the data set to which a component belongs.
An instance of the DataDescription class that describes the form/structure of a data item.
An id for the data component, could be a DAL-identififier or so.
The name for a DataComponent. Multiple alternative names are also allowed.
Date/time when the data component (individual data element or the complete set) was created.

The validity gives an expiration date (or a timespan?) to indicate the time range in which the data (values) are valid. This is mainly important for ambient conditions (seeing, moon light, etc.) and instrument characteristics, since these are functions of time.

This class covers data sets like RAVE-DR4 with its databases and database tables or any other collection of data. The data types can be mixed, e.g. a parameter plus n image files. The structure of the collection must be described in the corresponding DataCollectionDescription.

If pieces of data have the same origin, i.e. were produced by the same activity, they can be grouped to a data set. We decided to leave it to the person/tool recording provenance to decide how detailed a data set shall be separated into individual items.
Storage specifies where the (original) data produced by an activity can be found. This is not part of the Provenance Data Model (therefore the different coloring).
A reference to a file path, URL resource, .... where a description of the DataComponent (or the DataComponent itself??) can be found. Is this covered already by "Storage"?
This class describes the form/structure of a data item.
Unique id for the DataDescription.
A free text describing the data format.

Data components which are not data sets are either represented as parameters or structured data. The Parameter sub-class of DataComponent contains a set of key-value pairs, for instance from a configuration or a log file.
The data type underlying a parameter.
Name of a parameter
The value of a Parameter instance of type real.
The value of a Parameter instance of string type.
StoredData are stored somewhere on disk, e.g. as a file or a database table. This is the "usual" type of data.
The format in which an instance of the StructuredData class is present.
An instance of the Storage class which tells where to locate a certain data component.
Describes the type of transient data, e.g. by using ucds.
A string giving the data type as a ucd.
Describes the type/structure of stored data, e.g. a description of the file format (fits), the parameters of an input file or the table columns in the database.
A string giving the format of a structured data element (e.g. description of the file format (fits, ascii, ...) or description of a database table)
A class for describing the quality of an Activity or DataComponent. The Quality object could just contain a list of possible keywords.

This class can be used to specify data that existed only for a certain time and was deleted already, but is still usefull to describe the provenance of an activity/another data set. E.g. a telescope pipeline may produce images in between after each processing step, but only the final image is stored permanently.
Link to the description of the temporary data
Describes the type/structure of temporary data.
Description of a data collection as a whole (including it's structure), contains references to descriptions of the individual parts.
Link to the description of the components of a DataSet.
This is the project responsible for executing an Activity (e.g. the RAVE collaboration). There could also be more than one project involved in an Activity.
A unique id of the project for referencing it from different Activities.
A string to specify the person in charge of the project which has performed a certain activity.
Name(s) of the project. Alternative names can also be given.
A string to specify the person in charge of the project which has performed a certain activity.
This class serves to specify the role that a DataComponent takes when used as input for an Activity.
This class serves to specify the role that a DataComponent takes when produced as result by an Activity.
Link from the result data to the activity by which it has been produced.
This class describes the different roles of input data required for a certain method, e.g. parameter, parameter file, fits-image, etc. in a format specific for just this method.
This is the role a DataComponent can have for this method.
This class describes the different roles of result data typical for a certain method, e.g. fits-image, binary files etc. in a format specific for just this method.
A DataDescription contains a link to the Method that describes the Activity that generated the data.
This is the role a DataComponent can have for this method.
The link between a Method, i.e. the description of an Activity and its data descriptions. Not sure, if we need the link back from resultDataDescriptions to the creating activity method.
